Preparing data

The dataset come from Alarashi (2016), original (left) and cleaned (right)

Isolating objects

The function separate_single_artefacts() from the forked outlineR R package allows to separate objects (ie blobs) from the cleaned contact sheet and to save them in a new folder (outpath). Since some of the photographs beads show some light hues, the threshold has to be very high (thres = "99%"), we suppress all objects having an area below 10 pixel (min.area = 10)

separate_single_artefacts(inpath = inpath,
                          outpath = outpath,
                          thres = "99%",
                          min.area = 10)
## 
  |                                                                            
  |                                                                      |   0%[1] "nb of object before rm small ones: 444"

Converting to “Out” “Coo” objects

Convert to “Out” “Coo” objects with the R package Momocs

lf <- list.files(outpath, full.names=TRUE)
idfs <- as.factor(gsub("[^0-9]", "", lf))
fac <- data.frame(idf = idfs)
coo <- import_jpg(lf)

Shape analysis

Description

panel(beads, names = "idf", fac="idf")

beads.centered <- coo_center(beads)
stack(beads.centered, fac="idf", title = "beads centered")

beads.centered.scaled <- coo_scale(beads.centered)
stack(beads.centered.scaled, fac="idf", title = "beads centered and scaled")

PCA

beads.f <- efourier(beads)
beads.p <- PCA(beads.f)
plot(beads.p)

Symmetry

The symmetry index vary between 0 (no symetry) to 1 (perfectly symetric) (Iwata et al. 1998)

beads.s <- symmetry(beads.f)
sym.values <- as.factor(round(as.numeric(beads.s[, 'sym']), 2))
panel(beads, names = sym.values, fac="idf")

References

Alarashi, Hala. 2016. “Butterfly Beads in the Neolithic Near East: Evolution, Technology and Socio-Cultural Implications.” Cambridge Archaeological Journal 26 (3): 493–512.
Iwata, Hiroyoshi, Satoshi Niikura, Seiji Matsuura, Yasushi Takano, and Yasuo Ukai. 1998. “Evaluation of Variation of Root Shape of Japanese Radish (Raphanus Sativus l.) Based on Image Analysis Using Elliptic Fourier Descriptors.” Euphytica 102 (2): 143–49.
